The paper deals with topological data analysis, which involves computational geometry and discrete mathematics. The focus is on sparse filtrations, which are commonly used in computational topology. Therefore, cs.CG (Computational Geometry) and cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) are the most likely sub-categories. The paper also presents an algorithm, which falls under cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.SI (Social and Information Networks). Finally, the paper discusses the generalization of the results to different types of filtrations, which is related to cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory).
